In terms of the ferocity of the protests in the U.S., how much of it was due to the fact that we were fighting a Communist insurgency?  Think about this.  What if the politicians of the 60s had injected our military into South Africa, fighting in support of the ANC, and the war dragged on as long, and the casualties on all sides were as enormous.  Would the protests have been as great?  Would there have been any protests at all?  I don't think so.  The only protesters would have been branded as racists.<br><br>
Why did the protests diminish so greatly once the draft was abolished?  Were we really protesting a war?<br><br>
When I got my draft notice, my parents urged me to move to Canada.  During my year in Vietnam, they got tear gassed along with the college students.  Once I came home, and my brothers &quot;won the lottery,&quot; their activism stopped.<br><br>
In my opinion, the flames of protest were fanned by by leftist elitists.  Their pet form of government was being threatened.  Think about this-- there were more protests over our support of the contras in Nicaragua, a war in which no American G.I. blood was shed, than there were over our offensive in Desert Storm.  The difference, in my opinion, was the enemy.  Saddam is not a Communist.<br><br>

